            <!-- Section content -->
            <table role="presentation" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0" width="100%">
              <tr>
                <td style="padding:32px 40px 36px;" class="mobile-pad">

                  <!-- Headline -->
                  <h2 class="content-h2" style="margin:0 0 8px;font-family:-apple-system,BlinkMacSystemFont,'Segoe UI',Roboto,Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:24px;font-weight:800;color:#1a1a1a;line-height:1.25;">You're selling to 11 people.<br>You've only met 4 of them.</h2>
                  <p style="margin:0 0 20px;font-family:-apple-system,BlinkMacSystemFont,'Segoe UI',Roboto,Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:13px;font-weight:600;color:#C8392A;letter-spacing:0.5px;text-transform:uppercase;">The hidden buying committee killing B2B deals</p>

                  <p style="margin:0 0 16px;font-family:-apple-system,BlinkMacSystemFont,'Segoe UI',Roboto,Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:15px;line-height:1.75;color:#444444;">
                    I've spent years selling into manufacturing and industrial companies. The pattern I keep seeing: most B2B teams map their visible committee and call it done. They've never heard of the shadow committee. That's why their deals die.
                  </p>

                  <!-- Pull quote -->
                  <table role="presentation" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0" width="100%" style="margin:24px 0;">
                    <tr>
                      <td style="border-left:3px solid #C8392A;padding:12px 20px;background-color:#fdf6f5;border-radius:0 6px 6px 0;">
                        <p style="margin:0;font-family:-apple-system,BlinkMacSystemFont,'Segoe UI',Roboto,Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:16px;line-height:1.65;color:#1a1a1a;font-style:italic;font-weight:500;">
                          "The ones with real power aren't even in the meetings. You're taking your one message, your one position statement, and bringing it through the entire buying committee. That doesn't work."
                        </p>
                        <p style="margin:10px 0 0;font-family:-apple-system,BlinkMacSystemFont,'Segoe UI',Roboto,Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:12px;font-weight:700;color:#C8392A;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:1px;">Bill Murphy, Founder &amp; Chief Strategist · Colony Spark</p>
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                  </table>

                  <p style="margin:0 0 20px;font-family:-apple-system,BlinkMacSystemFont,'Segoe UI',Roboto,Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:15px;line-height:1.75;color:#444444;">
                    I break the real buying structure into three layers. Most teams only see one of them.
                  </p>

                  <!-- Layer 1 -->
                  <table role="presentation" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0" width="100%" style="margin-bottom:16px;">
                    <tr>
                      <td style="padding:18px 20px;background-color:#f9f9f9;border-radius:6px;border-top:2px solid #1a1a1a;">
                        <p style="margin:0 0 6px;font-family:-apple-system,BlinkMacSystemFont,'Segoe UI',Roboto,Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:800;letter-spacing:2px;color:#888888;text-transform:uppercase;">LAYER 1</p>
                        <p style="margin:0 0 6px;font-family:-apple-system,BlinkMacSystemFont,'Segoe UI',Roboto,Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:15px;font-weight:800;color:#1a1a1a;">The Visible Committee</p>
                        <p style="margin:0;font-family:-apple-system,BlinkMacSystemFont,'Segoe UI',Roboto,Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:14px;line-height:1.65;color:#555555;">VP of Operations, CFO, IT Director. These are the meetings you're getting. The CFO could be nodding along in your pitch while calculating if the board needs approval. For a $500K software purchase, that's another 3 months minimum.</p>
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                  </table>

                  <!-- Layer 2 -->
                  <table role="presentation" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0" width="100%" style="margin-bottom:16px;">
                    <tr>
                      <td style="padding:18px 20px;background-color:#f9f9f9;border-radius:6px;border-top:2px solid #C8392A;">
                        <p style="margin:0 0 6px;font-family:-apple-system,BlinkMacSystemFont,'Segoe UI',Roboto,Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:800;letter-spacing:2px;color:#C8392A;text-transform:uppercase;">LAYER 2</p>
                        <p style="margin:0 0 6px;font-family:-apple-system,BlinkMacSystemFont,'Segoe UI',Roboto,Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:15px;font-weight:800;color:#1a1a1a;">The Shadow Committee</p>
                        <p style="margin:0 0 10px;font-family:-apple-system,BlinkMacSystemFont,'Segoe UI',Roboto,Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:14px;line-height:1.65;color:#555555;">The people who never get on a vendor call but influence everything:</p>
                        <p style="margin:0 0 6px;font-family:-apple-system,BlinkMacSystemFont,'Segoe UI',Roboto,Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:14px;line-height:1.65;color:#555555;"><strong style="color:#1a1a1a;">The plant manager.</strong> Been there 20 years. Influences 73% of tech decisions but attends 0% of vendor calls. Has a direct line to the CEO. Two words from him can kill your deal: "this disrupts production."</p>
                        <p style="margin:0 0 6px;font-family:-apple-system,BlinkMacSystemFont,'Segoe UI',Roboto,Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:14px;line-height:1.65;color:#555555;"><strong style="color:#1a1a1a;">The legacy IT guy.</strong> Built the patchwork of custom scripts keeping everything running. When he says "this doesn't work with our system," the deal is dead.</p>
                        <p style="margin:0;font-family:-apple-system,BlinkMacSystemFont,'Segoe UI',Roboto,Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:14px;line-height:1.65;color:#555555;"><strong style="color:#1a1a1a;">The production supervisor.</strong> Controls the workers who'll actually use what you're selling. In companies doing $10-50M, this could be the owner's first hire. Easy place for quiet sabotage.</p>
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                  </table>

                  <!-- Layer 3 -->
                  <table role="presentation" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0" width="100%" style="margin-bottom:24px;">
                    <tr>
                      <td style="padding:18px 20px;background-color:#f9f9f9;border-radius:6px;border-top:2px solid #888888;">
                        <p style="margin:0 0 6px;font-family:-apple-system,BlinkMacSystemFont,'Segoe UI',Roboto,Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:800;letter-spacing:2px;color:#888888;text-transform:uppercase;">LAYER 3</p>
                        <p style="margin:0 0 6px;font-family:-apple-system,BlinkMacSystemFont,'Segoe UI',Roboto,Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:15px;font-weight:800;color:#1a1a1a;">The Political Layer</p>
                        <p style="margin:0 0 6px;font-family:-apple-system,BlinkMacSystemFont,'Segoe UI',Roboto,Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:14px;line-height:1.65;color:#555555;"><strong style="color:#1a1a1a;">The 25-year executive retiring in 18 months.</strong> Pension depends on no major failures. He slow-walks everything to next quarter. Every quarter.</p>
                        <p style="margin:0 0 6px;font-family:-apple-system,BlinkMacSystemFont,'Segoe UI',Roboto,Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:14px;line-height:1.65;color:#555555;"><strong style="color:#1a1a1a;">Your "champion" who needs a quick win.</strong> Pushing too hard. Their ambition creates internal backlash. They can actually hurt your deal.</p>
                        <p style="margin:0;font-family:-apple-system,BlinkMacSystemFont,'Segoe UI',Roboto,Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:14px;line-height:1.65;color:#555555;"><strong style="color:#1a1a1a;">The owner's inner circle.</strong> Golf buddies. A spouse. Long-time customers at dinner parties telling the owner "don't change a thing." Never in a meeting. Always in the owner's ear.</p>
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                  </table>

                  <!-- The counterintuitive move -->
                  <p style="margin:0 0 8px;font-family:-apple-system,BlinkMacSystemFont,'Segoe UI',Roboto,Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:17px;font-weight:800;color:#1a1a1a;">The counterintuitive move</p>
                  <p style="margin:0 0 16px;font-family:-apple-system,BlinkMacSystemFont,'Segoe UI',Roboto,Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:15px;line-height:1.75;color:#444444;">
                    The companies cutting 12-month cycles down to 6 didn't start at the C-suite. They went straight to the plant manager. Phase one priced under $50K, no board approval needed, one production line, one measurable improvement. Get the plant manager to say yes today. Then let the results do the selling up the chain.
                  </p>
                  <p style="margin:0 0 24px;font-family:-apple-system,BlinkMacSystemFont,'Segoe UI',Roboto,Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;font-size:15px;line-height:1.75;color:#444444;">
                    Crawl, walk, run: $45K pilot, then full plant rollout, then enterprise deployment. Each phase builds trust and reduces risk. By the time you're asking for the big contract, you're the incumbent.
                  </p>

